    {
        "content": "<p>firstly, this seems like a strange construction so let me <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/XY_problem\">#xy</a>...<br>\nSecondly, have you considered changing <code>piInst</code> to <code>{β : α → Type v}</code>?</p>",
        "id": 568699085,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1768776129
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No, I want to have <code>piInst</code> to be as general as possible, so it can apply to situations whether you have <code>Sort v</code></p>",
        "id": 568699127,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Arnez",
        "timestamp": 1768776191
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you're curious, this is for computability stuff and <code>MyClass.Rel n x</code> is basically a generalized form of <code>n = Encodable.encode x</code></p>",
        "id": 568699180,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Arnez",
        "timestamp": 1768776268
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>aha...<br>\nin that case, i think that having <code>proofInst</code> around is bad from lean's POV. in particular, talking about encoding things in <code>Sort u</code> in a universal way (as <code>proofInst</code> does) is always going to clash with an instance for pi types.<br>\nInstead, i think it will be better to either:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>not have this kind of instance at all for <code>Prop</code> values, because any time you use <code>propext</code> you can get non-defeq diamonds showing up</li>\n<li>if you must, only have instances for \"primitive\" <code>Prop</code>s e.g. <code>True</code>, <code>False</code>, <code>Exists</code>, etc...</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 568699586,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1768776866
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah that's also a solution I thought about; I definitely want to have an instance for <code>Prop</code>s (at least some that we know are safe I guess) for example to get <code>MyClass ((n : Nat) → n &lt; 7 → Nat)</code> and it would certainly be nice to automatically have this for all <code>Prop</code>s but it seems like this is always going to cause problems... oh well I guess I'll see how well it works to register for specific <code>Prop</code>s.</p>",
        "id": 568699850,
